# PrimeNG Federation Contract

This workspace is an Angular Nx module-federation sample using web-component remotes.
Keep the shell and every remote aligned to the same design-system contract.

## Required Provider

Every independently bootstrapped Angular app must call:

```ts
providePublicSectorPrimeNG()
```

Import it from `@public-sector/primeng-preset`. Do not call raw `providePrimeNG()`
inside apps or remotes.

## Token Sources

- Source tokens and baseline PrimeNG CSS variable fallbacks live in `packages/tokens`.
- PrimeNG preset/provider logic lives in `packages/primeng-preset`.
- Global app styles import `packages/tokens/src/tokens.css`.
- Shell controls dark mode by toggling `.p-dark` on `document.documentElement`.

## Federation Runtime

The shell loads remotes from `module-federation.manifest.json`:

- Shell: `4200`
- Services: `4201`
- Reporting: `4202`
- Admin: `4203`
- QA: `4204`

Use one dev-server owner. Prefer `pnpm start:all`, then verify with:

```bash
pnpm verify:fed
```

## PrimeNG Reintroduction Rule

Some PrimeNG hosts rendered as blank raw tags when they were used as route-critical
or shared-wrapper content. Reintroduce PrimeNG components one family at a time:

1. Verify the direct remote URL.
2. Verify the shell-composed route.
3. Run `pnpm verify:fed`.
4. Only then move the pattern into a shared wrapper.

Current safe smoke tests in `/qa`: `p-tag`, outlined `p-button`, `p-table`,
`p-dialog` opened from a native trigger, and isolated `p-card`.

Prefer stable token-styled native panels for route-critical content until the
PrimeNG host is proven reliable in both direct and shell-composed views. Avoid
promoting a PrimeNG host into a shared wrapper until the raw host passes first.

Reference: https://primeng.dev/llms/llms-full.txt
